[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So you can see right there. First off, whenever you run a command, it\'s inside of its own little block. This is the first thing I like to introduce inside of Warp is block editing. This is something you may not'

[05:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have seen before working with other terminals. So let me run a few commands to really give you the picture of what\'s going on. So I went to one directory, then I went to another. And now I\'m going to run a third command just so we have something in here. Like maybe I'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want to switch back over to the main line or something like that. Master on this project specifically. So let me switch over to that. So yeah, now we ran a few commands in our terminal. As you can see, it works roughly the same as any other terminal'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that you have tried. Right off the bat though, you will notice it also gives us some auto suggestions. These are built into Warp by default. So you don\'t have to configure these yourself. You don\'t have to learn anything about shells. You'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t have to learn anything about all the complicated tools you might have heard about on Twitter or Reddit or whatever else. You just install the Warp terminal and you get this stuff. You get auto completions just built into it. And you also get blocks for every output'

[06:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'built into this. What are blocks? Blocks are just a combination of the input and output of a command in a little highlightable section. So you can see right here, every time I click on one of these guys, it doesn\'t just highlight'

[06:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the individual line. It\'s actually highlighting the entire block, the input and the output of a command. And this is really convenient for first off navigating around your terminal. If you hold down the command key or the control'

[07:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or control shift key on Windows, you can hit the up arrow and down arrow to quickly walk through all of the commands that you are running. And let me show you how this is especially useful if you have like'

[07:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'longer commands that you\'re trying to iterate through. So here\'s a long stack trace of running cargo run or something like that. You can see if you just hit command up arrow, you can actually jump to the top of whatever that command was and also jump to the bottom. So here I\'m'

[07:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like jumping to the bottom of this long output. Then I\'m jumping up to the command that was above that output. So I don\'t have to scroll really far. I can just command up arrow and quickly navigate through everything, which is really convenient. I haven\'t really seen'

[07:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a terminal do it quite like that. It\'s something Warp\'s had built in since the beginning, I think. Another thing that you\'ll notice is you get sticky headers. So if it\'s a long stack trace, you can still see what the directory, the branch, and the command were along with the execution time. Kind'

[07:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of convenient. And you also get some controls up here that make it easier to work with the output of that command. way is to attach it to an agent to ask'

[08:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the agent something about that command. But we also have this one that\'s worth talking about, filter block output. This is really nice because it\'ll let you filter down specific lines of an output without having to use like command find'

[08:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and like look for specific lines. This is especially useful if you\'re running a dev server and you want to look for specific flags. Let me try running cargo run and use filter on it right away. So here I have a live running command and'

[08:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'maybe I just want to filter down the logs to anything relating to the asset cache. I could do something like asset. And now it\'ll just give me the lines in this running output that relate to assets. And I can click to just dismiss'

[08:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that. So now it\'ll only show me those even while the command is running, which is kind of nice. So now you don\'t have to look through a long stack trace in order to look for key terms. You can just only see the key terms that you are'

[09:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interested in while it is running. Yeah, probably over explained filtering for y\'all, but that\'s filtering. It\'s very convenient. And we also have this little ellipsis menu. There\'s a few other options inside of here that you'

[09:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can play with. One of them is, you know, finding within the block, which is a more traditional like I want to see the results without filtering down the lines. Of course you have that as well. But you can scope it to the specific block. So you don\'t get results from other terminal output. You'

[09:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can only search for things specifically inside of here. So I\'m looking for like compiling inside of here without filtering it down up there. You can also do Warp editor and now it\'s just showing you that result without matching on'

[09:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other results. You can also copy just the command or the output, which is kind of nice. So if you just wanted to copy the command that was run, you can do that. So I could just copy the cargo run phrase. There we'

[09:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'go. I do that all the time. You can also just copy the output if you want to share the stack trace with someone and without the input involved. So, you don\'t have to like drag and highlight whatever that stack trace was. You can just kind of click on the block, which'

[10:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is this whole thing, and then you can say copy output with a right click, and there you go. Uh you can also share it, though. So, if you wanted to take that stack trace and put it in a web link instead of just the plain text output, we\'ll generate a web'

[10:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'link for you. This is really great. Uh and we support like megabytes of logs if you really, really need them. So, if it\'s a long stack trace that you can\'t just paste into a Slack conversation, you can generate a link instead, and you'

[10:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can give it a title if you want to, like Rust output. You can create the link, and now this is something that you could share with your team. And it\'s just kind of ready to go. Really nice. Um you can also see there you have manage shared blocks to look through'

[10:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your history if that\'s something that you care about. Um so, yeah, that\'s really like the core essentials of navigating around Warp. Uh you can run commands how you would other terminals. You have built-in auto-complete. You don\'t have to install it or anything. Uh you can navigate'

[10:50] [scene:talk]
