[52:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Um people are starting to put stuff into cloud runners because A, they might need to trigger an agent not from their terminal. Like maybe you want to trigger an agent from a Slack conversation. Maybe you just wanted to run every'

[52:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'morning and do something. Like we have a weekly job to clean up old feature flags or we have a daily job that does competitive analysis and uses web search to like search for competitors and ping us on Slack with stuff. If you\'re trying'

[53:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to build automations like that, you can\'t run it on your local hardware, at least not easily. Of course you could build a tunnel or something like that. But the safest way to do is have some sort of external machine that you can spin up and run a job inside of. Uh and'

[53:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ideally that\'s a serverless machine too. So that for every job you get your own little sandbox for the agent to run around in. Uh so that sandboxing feature and also the scheduling of that agent is'

[53:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that Warp help Warp helps you with now. Uh with a cloud environment setup that\'s called Oz. So for anyone who\'s like wondering what is it at a high level, if you want to investigate it after this'

[53:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stream, this is the URL cuz we\'re not going to have a lot of time to go through it. But I\'m going to give you just a high level overview of what the cloud part is to see if it\'s at all useful to you. Um so cloud environments. How do you set'

[53:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them up? Um so first off, if you wanted to run an agent from an automation for example or from some scheduled job, you need to have an environment. And [snorts] an environment is just the set of tools'

[54:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that the agent has access to when it acts on that automation. So you might set up a job every morning with a prompt or a skill, which is just like a fancy big prompt in a markdown file. And [snorts] you need that agent to have'

[54:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'access to your code base for example. Like you need it to access your server and your client code bases. And then maybe it needs web search. Maybe it needs node so that it can run the test suite. Like it it\'s the set of config.'

[54:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In other words, a Docker config. And that\'s exactly what Warp environments are. So you can set these up with Docker files. You can act You can actually have an agent set up the environment for you.'

[54:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then once it\'s set up, you can trigger jobs inside of it. So first off, I\'ll just show you all the environments that I have. If you want to create an environment, you run slash create environment and that will open up an agent to create a cloud environment for'

[55:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you. And once you have all of them, you can look at your environments by running slash cloud agent. So this takes you over to this nested view that looks a lot like the other agent stuff that we\'ve been looking at. But'

[55:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the one difference is you don\'t see your current directory. You see a cloud environment. And this is going to be a list of all the environments that you set up in the past. And this is just a Docker image that describes the tooling that\'s available and the code'

[55:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'repositories to clone down whenever you go into this thing. So you can see I actually have an environment for this repo that we\'ve been working on. I also have a number of environments inside of here for for example, Warpy Sheets. This is a fun one. This is a clone of Google'

[55:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
